{"title_page": "Belford, Northumberland", "text_new": "{{Short description|Village and civil parish in Northumberland, England}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n:''This article is about the place in Northumberland, England. For other places with the same name see [[Belford (disambiguation)|Belford]]''\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image_name = High Street, Belford.jpg \n|static_image_caption = High Street, Belford\n|country = England \n|official_name = Belford\n|coordinates = {{coord|55.598|-1.828|display=inline,title}}\n| population = 1,258\n| population_ref = ''(2011)''\n| unitary_england=        [[Northumberland County Council|Northumberland]]\n|lieutenancy_england=    [[Northumberland]]\n|region = North East England\n|constituency_westminster = [[Berwick-upon-Tweed (UK Parliament constituency)|Berwick-upon-Tweed]]\n|post_town = BELFORD\n|postcode_district = NE70\n|postcode_area = NE \n|dial_code = 01668\n|os_grid_reference = NU108339 \n}}\n'''Belford''' is a village and [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in Northumberland, England, about halfway between [[Alnwick]] and [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], a few miles inland from the east coast and just off the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|Great North Road]], the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]]. At the 2001 census it had a population of 1,055,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790477 |title=Census 2001 |access-date=2 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613015439/http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790477 |archive-date=13 June 2011 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> increasing to 1,258 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11120574&c=NE70+7EU&d=16&e=62&g=6452850&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1435240405407&enc=1|title=Parish population 2011|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nBelford is surrounded by rich pastoral farmland, and to the west of the village is found one of the better [[rock climbing]] locations in the county, Bowden Doors.\n\n== Governance ==\nBelford is in the [[United Kingdom constituencies|parliamentary constituency]] of [[Berwick-upon-Tweed (UK Parliament constituency)|Berwick-upon-Tweed]] and is currently served by [[Anne-Marie Trevelyan]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]). Belford is served by [[Northumberland County Council]].\n\n== Economy ==\nThe area attracts tourists and there are also a number of businesses based in Belford.\n\n== Landmarks ==\n\n===Belford Hall===\n[[File:Belford Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1172079.jpg|left|thumb|Belford Hall]]\n[[Belford Hall]] is a [[Grade I listed building]], an 18th-century mansion house.\n\nThe Manor of Belford was acquired by the Dixon family in 1726 and in 1752 Abraham Dixon built a mansion house in a [[Palladian style]] to a design by architect [[James Paine (architect)|James Paine]]. In 1770 heiress Margaret Dixon married William Brown. Their daughter later married [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] merchant, Lt. Col. William Clark, [[Deputy Lieutenant]] and [[High Sheriff of Northumberland]]\nwho, in 1818, remodelled the house and added two new wings, with the assistance of architect [[John Dobson (architect)|John Dobson]].\n\nAn extensive park, created in the mid 18th century, retains several original features and has been designated a [[conservation area]]. An 18th-century folly in the park is a [[Grade II listed building]]. During [[World War II]] the Hall was requisitioned by the [[British Army|Army]] and thereafter became neglected and dilapidated. In the 1980s it was acquired by the Northern Heritage Trust, renovated and restored and converted to residential flats.\n\n[[File:Spindlestone Ducket Mill.jpg|thumb|Spindlestone Ducket Mill]]\n\n===Spindlestone Ducket Mill===\nThis is located about 3&nbsp;km east of Belford, and is an 18th-century tapering cylindrical stone tower with a conical roof of Welsh slate. Its usage is uncertain, being sometimes classified as a [[windmill]] and sometimes as a [[dovecote]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-409365-spindlestone-ducket-easington|work=British Listed Buildings|date=22 December 1969|title=Spindlestone Ducket, Easington|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Westhall===\n[[Westhall, Northumberland|Westhall]] is a privately owned Victorian house built in the style of the castellated fortified house that it replaced on the same site. The moat that surrounded the original building can still clearly be seen. It is now in use as a farmhouse.\n\n==History==\nFor much of the Middle Ages, Belford was at the forefront of the ongoing border conflict between the Scots and the English and it is believed that only Well House escaped damage or destruction at the hands of Scottish raiders. In 1272 it is recorded that [[Walter de Huntercombe, 1st Baron Huntercombe|Walter de Huntercombe]], the Lord of the Manor, was charged with 'assisting pirates'! They had seized, by force, goods belonging to some wealthy Spanish merchants and landed with their booty on Holy Island.<ref>{{cite book|last=Local History Society|first=Belford and District|title=Bygone Belford|year=2010|publisher=Stenlake Publishing|location=Catrine, Ayrshire|isbn=9781840335170|pages=3\u20134|url=http://www.stenlake.co.uk/books/view_book.php?ref=638}}</ref>\n\nIn 1726, A wealthy city merchant, [[Abraham Dixon]] bought the Belford Estate. He made improvements which enhanced the fortunes of its inhabitants significantly including purchasing a licence in 1742 allowing him to hold a weekly market and two annual fairs at Belford. His son continued improvements after his death in 1746 and by 1770, a visitor was able to report the existence of a woollen mill, a tannery, collieries and a 'large lime kiln'. Improvements to hygiene were also imposed upon the inhabitants with the forced removal of muck heaps from the houses and the banning of swine.<ref>{{cite book|last=Local History Society|first=Belford and District|title=Bygone Belford|year=2010|publisher=Stenlake Publishing|location=Catrine, Ayrshire|isbn=9781840335170|pages=3\u20135|url=http://www.stenlake.co.uk/books/view_book.php?ref=638}}</ref>\n\nLarger market towns have gradually replaced Belford in importance and  the location of the station outside of the town itself did nothing to halt a gradual decline in its fortunes since the end of the 19th century. Many of the features of its heyday have been retained however.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Belford railway station 1864386 0c5085c4.jpg|thumb|left|The former [[Belford (Northumberland) railway station|Belford railway station]] in 1965]]\nBelford was for many years a coaching stop on the main [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1 road]] from London to [[Edinburgh]], which passed through the village.<ref name=\"Lily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lilycottagebelford.co.uk/belford_village.htm |title=Belford |accessdate=27 January 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125025303/http://www.lilycottagebelford.co.uk/belford_village.htm |archivedate=25 November 2010 |df= }}</ref> However, in 1983 a bypass was opened, and, freed from the constant traffic and pollution, the village could hold events on the High Street and in the Market Place once again.\n\n[[Belford (Northumberland) railway station|Belford railway station]] opened on 29 March 1847. Freight services ceased on 7 June 1965 and the station finally closed for passenger services on 20 January 1968.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northumbrian-railways.co.uk/index.php?page=belford|title=Belford|work=Northumbrian Railways|accessdate=27 January 2011}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, on 8 February 2010 Northumberland County Council agreed plans to resume passenger services by constructing a new platform, access and car parking.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berwick-advertiser.co.uk/news/local-headlines/county_council_go_ahead_for_belford_station_plan_1_234059|title=County council go-ahead for Belford station plan|work=the Berwick Advertiser|date=10 February 2010|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nSt Mary's Church of England Voluntary Aided Middle School in Williams Way, Belford<ref name=DES>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/SI/si2006/uksi_20061905_en.pdf|title=The Belford St Mary's Church of England Voluntary Aided Middle School (Designation as having a Religious Character) Order 2006|work=Department for Education and Skills Statutory Instrument|date=12 July 2006|author=Shan Scott|accessdate=1 February 2011}}</ref> provides mainstream education for just under 100 boys and girls aged from nine to thirteen.<ref name=GSG>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodschoolsguide.co.uk/school/st-marys-church-of-england-middle-school.html|work=The Good Schools Guide|title=St Mary's Church of England Middle School|year=2011|accessdate=1 February 2011}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Churches==\nThe [[Church of England parish church]] of St Mary is an [[English Gothic architecture#Early English Gothic|Early English Gothic]] stone building on a hill overlooking the village. Its tower has two bells.<ref name=Kelly>{{cite web |title=Kelly's Directory of Northumberland and Durham |year=1873 |page=495 |url= http://www.ancestral-indexes.co.uk/misc/NBL/BAM/BAM-BFD.htm#church |accessdate=1 February 2011}}</ref> St Mary's was built in about 1200, rebuilt in 1615, and renovated in 1700 and 1828.<ref name=cam>{{cite web |url= http://www.northumberland-cam.com/churches/belford.htm |title=Parish Church of St. Mary, Belford, Northumberland |work=Northumberland Cam |accessdate=1 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nBelford has also a [[United Reformed Church]].<ref name=urch>{{cite web |url=http://www.belfordvillage.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=13&Itemid=12 |title=United Reformed Church Belford |work=Belford Village |year=2011 |accessdate=1 February 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905073252/http://www.belfordvillage.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=13&Itemid=12 |archivedate=5 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Sports ==\nIn 2008, Belford Junior Football Club was awarded the [[Queen's Award for Voluntary Service]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.queensawardvoluntary.gov.uk/winners/northeast08.html | archive-url= http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090107233612/http%3A//www.queensawardvoluntary.gov.uk/winners/northeast08.html |url-status = dead| archive-date= 7 January 2009 | title= 2008 Winners, North East | work= The Queen's Award for Voluntary Service | publisher= [[Cabinet Office|The Cabinet Office]] | accessdate= 8 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== Public services ==\nBelford has an active local history society which has published a series of books in recent years, the latest being 'Bygone Belford' (2010). In 1995 the society carried out A Survey of Belford. A booklet was published and the text of the survey is available online (see external links). A similar survey had been conducted quarter of a century earlier, in 1970.\n\n== Notable people ==\n'''Births:'''\n*[[Marcus Dods (theologian born 1834)|Marcus Dods]], Scottish divine and biblical scholar, was born in Belford in 1834<ref name=GSP>{{cite web|url=http://firstbaptistchurchforterie.org/web_documents/more_like_the_master_july_2010.pdf|author=Gary Screaton Page|title=More Like The Master|year=2009|accessdate=1 February 2011}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*[[Robert Mason (Liberal politician)]] was born in Belford in 1857 and was a member of parliament from 1918 to 1922\n*[[Michael Clark (Canadian politician)]] was born in Belford in 1861 and moved to Canada in 1902\n*[[William Coldstream|Sir William Coldstream]], artist, was born in Belford, 28 February 1908<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stanford.edu/group/auden/cgi-bin/auden/individual.php?pid=I22600&ged=auden-bicknell.ged |title=Sir William Coldstream|accessdate=4 November 2011}}</ref>                                                                       \n*[[William Wilson Allen]], VC (Rorke's Drift) lived at Belford Moor, (now Belford Mains) as a child.\n*[[Lucy Bronze]], an English female footballer who plays for Everton Ladies, lived for a time in Belford\n                                                                                      \n'''Deaths:'''\n*[[Geoffrey Hornblower Cock]], MC, World War I flying ace died in Belford in 1980\n\n==Belford in the media==\nBelford is mentioned in \"The Great Race\" episode of the 1970s sitcom ''[[Whatever Happened to the Likely Lads?]]'' when Terry claims he overtook Bob in a bicycle race by cycling through the town whereas Bob used the A1 bypass.\n\nBelford was featured on the TV programme Countryfile on 10 April 1994, following a telephone call to the BBC by a resident. At the time, like other villages in the area, Belford was suffering from an increasing number of power cuts. Inspired by the programme a group was formed and, after much campaigning and lobbying, the electricity supply was improved.\n\nBelford again achieved momentary fame in April 2000 when protests about the closure of Barclays Bank in the village were picked up and used by the mainstream media to illustrate stories of rural decline brought about by bank branch closures. Until the 1980s there was a branch of Lloyds Bank, with limited opening hours towards the end.\n\nDuring the 2000s a series of major floods affected the villagers causing widespread damage to property. This led to the development of a flood protection scheme for the village termed Natural Flood Management which was developed by a Newcastle University research group in conjunction with the Environment Agency flood levy team\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Middleton Hall, Middleton, Northumberland|Middleton Hall]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Belford, Northumberland}}\n*[http://www.northofthetyne.co.uk/BelfordCastle.html Images of Belford Castle site with history notes]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/705062.stm Village 'devastated' at losing bank] \u2013 news from the [[BBC]] in April 2000\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050104061536/http://www.ukclimbing.com/databases/crags/craginfo.html?id=824 Bowden Doors] described, at UKClimbing.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081031102144/http://www.genuki.bpears.org.uk/NBL/Belford/index.html GENUKI] (Accessed: 1 November 2008) \t\n*[http://communities.northumberland.gov.uk/Belford.htm Northumberland Communities] (Accessed: 1 November 2008)\n*[http://www.nnouk.com/belford-northumberland.shtml North Northumberland Online] \u2013 a page about Belford and the online version of A Survey of Belford 1995\n*[http://www.berwick-advertiser.co.uk/news/local-headlines/history_society_book_looks_back_on_bygone_belford_1_286546 Berwick Advertiser] \u2013 an article about 'Bygone Belford' \u2013 a book by Belford's local history society\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Northumberland]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n:''This article is about the place in Northumberland, England. For other places with the same name see [[Belford (disambiguation)|Belford]]''\n{{Infobox UK place\n|static_image_name = High Street, Belford.jpg \n|static_image_caption = High Street, Belford\n|country = England \n|official_name = Belford\n|coordinates = {{coord|55.598|-1.828|display=inline,title}}\n| population = 1,258\n| population_ref = ''(2011)''\n| unitary_england=        [[Northumberland County Council|Northumberland]]\n|lieutenancy_england=    [[Northumberland]]\n|region = North East England\n|constituency_westminster = [[Berwick-upon-Tweed (UK Parliament constituency)|Berwick-upon-Tweed]]\n|post_town = BELFORD\n|postcode_district = NE70\n|postcode_area = NE \n|dial_code = 01668\n|os_grid_reference = NU108339 \n}}\n'''Belford''' is a village and [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in Northumberland, England, about halfway between [[Alnwick]] and [[Berwick-upon-Tweed]], a few miles inland from the east coast and just off the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|Great North Road]], the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1]]. At the 2001 census it had a population of 1,055,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790477 |title=Census 2001 |access-date=2 August 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613015439/http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790477 |archive-date=13 June 2011 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> increasing to 1,258 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11120574&c=NE70+7EU&d=16&e=62&g=6452850&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1435240405407&enc=1|title=Parish population 2011|accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nBelford is surrounded by rich pastoral farmland, and to the west of the village is found one of the better [[rock climbing]] locations in the county, Bowden Doors.\n\n== Governance ==\nBelford is in the [[United Kingdom constituencies|parliamentary constituency]] of [[Berwick-upon-Tweed (UK Parliament constituency)|Berwick-upon-Tweed]] and is currently served by [[Anne-Marie Trevelyan]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]). Belford is served by [[Northumberland County Council]].\n\n== Economy ==\nThe area attracts tourists and there are also a number of businesses based in Belford.\n\n== Landmarks ==\n\n===Belford Hall===\n[[File:Belford Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1172079.jpg|left|thumb|Belford Hall]]\n[[Belford Hall]] is a [[Grade I listed building]], an 18th-century mansion house.\n\nThe Manor of Belford was acquired by the Dixon family in 1726 and in 1752 Abraham Dixon built a mansion house in a [[Palladian style]] to a design by architect [[James Paine (architect)|James Paine]]. In 1770 heiress Margaret Dixon married William Brown. Their daughter later married [[Newcastle upon Tyne]] merchant, Lt. Col. William Clark, [[Deputy Lieutenant]] and [[High Sheriff of Northumberland]]\nwho, in 1818, remodelled the house and added two new wings, with the assistance of architect [[John Dobson (architect)|John Dobson]].\n\nAn extensive park, created in the mid 18th century, retains several original features and has been designated a [[conservation area]]. An 18th-century folly in the park is a [[Grade II listed building]]. During [[World War II]] the Hall was requisitioned by the [[British Army|Army]] and thereafter became neglected and dilapidated. In the 1980s it was acquired by the Northern Heritage Trust, renovated and restored and converted to residential flats.\n\n[[File:Spindlestone Ducket Mill.jpg|thumb|Spindlestone Ducket Mill]]\n\n===Spindlestone Ducket Mill===\nThis is located about 3&nbsp;km east of Belford, and is an 18th-century tapering cylindrical stone tower with a conical roof of Welsh slate. Its usage is uncertain, being sometimes classified as a [[windmill]] and sometimes as a [[dovecote]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-409365-spindlestone-ducket-easington|work=British Listed Buildings|date=22 December 1969|title=Spindlestone Ducket, Easington|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Westhall===\n[[Westhall, Northumberland|Westhall]] is a privately owned Victorian house built in the style of the castellated fortified house that it replaced on the same site. The moat that surrounded the original building can still clearly be seen. It is now in use as a farmhouse.\n\n==History==\nFor much of the Middle Ages, Belford was at the forefront of the ongoing border conflict between the Scots and the English and it is believed that only Well House escaped damage or destruction at the hands of Scottish raiders. In 1272 it is recorded that [[Walter de Huntercombe, 1st Baron Huntercombe|Walter de Huntercombe]], the Lord of the Manor, was charged with 'assisting pirates'! They had seized, by force, goods belonging to some wealthy Spanish merchants and landed with their booty on Holy Island.<ref>{{cite book|last=Local History Society|first=Belford and District|title=Bygone Belford|year=2010|publisher=Stenlake Publishing|location=Catrine, Ayrshire|isbn=9781840335170|pages=3\u20134|url=http://www.stenlake.co.uk/books/view_book.php?ref=638}}</ref>\n\nIn 1726, A wealthy city merchant, [[Abraham Dixon]] bought the Belford Estate. He made improvements which enhanced the fortunes of its inhabitants significantly including purchasing a licence in 1742 allowing him to hold a weekly market and two annual fairs at Belford. His son continued improvements after his death in 1746 and by 1770, a visitor was able to report the existence of a woollen mill, a tannery, collieries and a 'large lime kiln'. Improvements to hygiene were also imposed upon the inhabitants with the forced removal of muck heaps from the houses and the banning of swine.<ref>{{cite book|last=Local History Society|first=Belford and District|title=Bygone Belford|year=2010|publisher=Stenlake Publishing|location=Catrine, Ayrshire|isbn=9781840335170|pages=3\u20135|url=http://www.stenlake.co.uk/books/view_book.php?ref=638}}</ref>\n\nLarger market towns have gradually replaced Belford in importance and  the location of the station outside of the town itself did nothing to halt a gradual decline in its fortunes since the end of the 19th century. Many of the features of its heyday have been retained however.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Belford railway station 1864386 0c5085c4.jpg|thumb|left|The former [[Belford (Northumberland) railway station|Belford railway station]] in 1965]]\nBelford was for many years a coaching stop on the main [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1 road]] from London to [[Edinburgh]], which passed through the village.<ref name=\"Lily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lilycottagebelford.co.uk/belford_village.htm |title=Belford |accessdate=27 January 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125025303/http://www.lilycottagebelford.co.uk/belford_village.htm |archivedate=25 November 2010 |df= }}</ref> However, in 1983 a bypass was opened, and, freed from the constant traffic and pollution, the village could hold events on the High Street and in the Market Place once again.\n\n[[Belford (Northumberland) railway station|Belford railway station]] opened on 29 March 1847. Freight services ceased on 7 June 1965 and the station finally closed for passenger services on 20 January 1968.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.northumbrian-railways.co.uk/index.php?page=belford|title=Belford|work=Northumbrian Railways|accessdate=27 January 2011}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, on 8 February 2010 Northumberland County Council agreed plans to resume passenger services by constructing a new platform, access and car parking.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berwick-advertiser.co.uk/news/local-headlines/county_council_go_ahead_for_belford_station_plan_1_234059|title=County council go-ahead for Belford station plan|work=the Berwick Advertiser|date=10 February 2010|accessdate=27 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Education ==\nSt Mary's Church of England Voluntary Aided Middle School in Williams Way, Belford<ref name=DES>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/SI/si2006/uksi_20061905_en.pdf|title=The Belford St Mary's Church of England Voluntary Aided Middle School (Designation as having a Religious Character) Order 2006|work=Department for Education and Skills Statutory Instrument|date=12 July 2006|author=Shan Scott|accessdate=1 February 2011}}</ref> provides mainstream education for just under 100 boys and girls aged from nine to thirteen.<ref name=GSG>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodschoolsguide.co.uk/school/st-marys-church-of-england-middle-school.html|work=The Good Schools Guide|title=St Mary's Church of England Middle School|year=2011|accessdate=1 February 2011}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Churches==\nThe [[Church of England parish church]] of St Mary is an [[English Gothic architecture#Early English Gothic|Early English Gothic]] stone building on a hill overlooking the village. Its tower has two bells.<ref name=Kelly>{{cite web |title=Kelly's Directory of Northumberland and Durham |year=1873 |page=495 |url= http://www.ancestral-indexes.co.uk/misc/NBL/BAM/BAM-BFD.htm#church |accessdate=1 February 2011}}</ref> St Mary's was built in about 1200, rebuilt in 1615, and renovated in 1700 and 1828.<ref name=cam>{{cite web |url= http://www.northumberland-cam.com/churches/belford.htm |title=Parish Church of St. Mary, Belford, Northumberland |work=Northumberland Cam |accessdate=1 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nBelford has also a [[United Reformed Church]].<ref name=urch>{{cite web |url=http://www.belfordvillage.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=13&Itemid=12 |title=United Reformed Church Belford |work=Belford Village |year=2011 |accessdate=1 February 2011 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110905073252/http://www.belfordvillage.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=category&layout=blog&id=13&Itemid=12 |archivedate=5 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Sports ==\nIn 2008, Belford Junior Football Club was awarded the [[Queen's Award for Voluntary Service]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.queensawardvoluntary.gov.uk/winners/northeast08.html | archive-url= http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090107233612/http%3A//www.queensawardvoluntary.gov.uk/winners/northeast08.html |url-status = dead| archive-date= 7 January 2009 | title= 2008 Winners, North East | work= The Queen's Award for Voluntary Service | publisher= [[Cabinet Office|The Cabinet Office]] | accessdate= 8 June 2008 }}</ref>\n\n== Public services ==\nBelford has an active local history society which has published a series of books in recent years, the latest being 'Bygone Belford' (2010). In 1995 the society carried out A Survey of Belford. A booklet was published and the text of the survey is available online (see external links). A similar survey had been conducted quarter of a century earlier, in 1970.\n\n== Notable people ==\n'''Births:'''\n*[[Marcus Dods (theologian born 1834)|Marcus Dods]], Scottish divine and biblical scholar, was born in Belford in 1834<ref name=GSP>{{cite web|url=http://firstbaptistchurchforterie.org/web_documents/more_like_the_master_july_2010.pdf|author=Gary Screaton Page|title=More Like The Master|year=2009|accessdate=1 February 2011}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*[[Robert Mason (Liberal politician)]] was born in Belford in 1857 and was a member of parliament from 1918 to 1922\n*[[Michael Clark (Canadian politician)]] was born in Belford in 1861 and moved to Canada in 1902\n*[[William Coldstream|Sir William Coldstream]], artist, was born in Belford, 28 February 1908<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stanford.edu/group/auden/cgi-bin/auden/individual.php?pid=I22600&ged=auden-bicknell.ged |title=Sir William Coldstream|accessdate=4 November 2011}}</ref>                                                                       \n*[[William Wilson Allen]], VC (Rorke's Drift) lived at Belford Moor, (now Belford Mains) as a child.\n*[[Lucy Bronze]], an English female footballer who plays for Everton Ladies, lived for a time in Belford\n                                                                                      \n'''Deaths:'''\n*[[Geoffrey Hornblower Cock]], MC, World War I flying ace died in Belford in 1980\n\n==Belford in the media==\nBelford is mentioned in \"The Great Race\" episode of the 1970s sitcom ''[[Whatever Happened to the Likely Lads?]]'' when Terry claims he overtook Bob in a bicycle race by cycling through the town whereas Bob used the A1 bypass.\n\nBelford was featured on the TV programme Countryfile on 10 April 1994, following a telephone call to the BBC by a resident. At the time, like other villages in the area, Belford was suffering from an increasing number of power cuts. Inspired by the programme a group was formed and, after much campaigning and lobbying, the electricity supply was improved.\n\nBelford again achieved momentary fame in April 2000 when protests about the closure of Barclays Bank in the village were picked up and used by the mainstream media to illustrate stories of rural decline brought about by bank branch closures. Until the 1980s there was a branch of Lloyds Bank, with limited opening hours towards the end.\n\nDuring the 2000s a series of major floods affected the villagers causing widespread damage to property. This led to the development of a flood protection scheme for the village termed Natural Flood Management which was developed by a Newcastle University research group in conjunction with the Environment Agency flood levy team\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Middleton Hall, Middleton, Northumberland|Middleton Hall]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Belford, Northumberland}}\n*[http://www.northofthetyne.co.uk/BelfordCastle.html Images of Belford Castle site with history notes]\n*[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/705062.stm Village 'devastated' at losing bank] \u2013 news from the [[BBC]] in April 2000\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050104061536/http://www.ukclimbing.com/databases/crags/craginfo.html?id=824 Bowden Doors] described, at UKClimbing.com\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081031102144/http://www.genuki.bpears.org.uk/NBL/Belford/index.html GENUKI] (Accessed: 1 November 2008) \t\n*[http://communities.northumberland.gov.uk/Belford.htm Northumberland Communities] (Accessed: 1 November 2008)\n*[http://www.nnouk.com/belford-northumberland.shtml North Northumberland Online] \u2013 a page about Belford and the online version of A Survey of Belford 1995\n*[http://www.berwick-advertiser.co.uk/news/local-headlines/history_society_book_looks_back_on_bygone_belford_1_286546 Berwick Advertiser] \u2013 an article about 'Bygone Belford' \u2013 a book by Belford's local history society\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Northumberland]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Add short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Belford,_Northumberland"}
{"title_page": "Paramasivan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Paramasivan\n| image          = Paramasivan.JPG\n| alt            = \n| director       = [[P. Vasu]]\n| producer       = S. Ramesh Babu\n| writer         = Pattukottai Prabakar'''(dialogues)'''\n| story          = [[Mahesh Bhatt]]\n| starring       = [[Ajith Kumar]]     \n  <br /> [[Laila Mehdin|Laila]]<br />[[Jayaram]]<br />[[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]]<br />[[Prakash Raj]]<br />\n| | music        = [[Vidyasagar (music director)|Vidyasagar]]\n| cinematography = [[Sekhar V. Joseph]]\n| editing        = [[Suresh Urs]]\n| studio         = Kanagarathna Movies<br />Samrat Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|2006|01|14|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 165 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Tamil| \n| \n}}\n'''''Paramasivan''''' ({{lang-en|Supreme Shiva}}) is a 2006 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil-language]] [[action thriller]] film directed by [[P. Vasu]] and produced by S. Ramesh Babu. The film features [[Ajith Kumar]] in the lead role with [[Laila Mehdin|Laila]], [[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]], [[Prakash Raj]] and [[Jayaram]] playing other pivotal roles. The synopsis is based on [[1998 Coimbatore bombings]]. It was released on 14 January 2006 to mixed reviews and declared as an above average grosser at the box office .<ref>[http://www.sify.com/movies/paramasivan-review-tamil-14120438.html Paramasivan review]. sify.com</ref><ref>Davis, Franko (10 November 2005) [http://www.nowrunning.com/movie/2613/tamil/paramasivan/627/review.htm Paramasivan review]. nowrunning.com</ref> The film was inspired from the [[Hindi language|Hindi-language]] film ''[[Kartoos]]'' (1999) starring [[Sanjay Dutt]], [[Jackie Shroff]] and [[Manisha Koirala]].\n\n==Plot==\nSubramaniyam Siva ([[Ajith Kumar]]) is in jail, awaiting the death sentence for killing corrupt and evil members of the police force who had killed his father SI Ganapathy ([[Rajesh (actor)|Rajesh]]) and sister. SP of Police ''Nethiadi'' Nandakumar ([[Prakash Raj]]) is an honest, fearless and upright police officer who has been given the mission to flush out the terrorist outfit behind the Coimbatore blasts. He decides to employ unconventional methods to fulfill his mission and engages Siva to assist him, renaming him Paramasivan, changing his look (cutting his long hair), and giving him a single-point agenda&nbsp;\u2013 trace out and erase the people responsible for the Coimbatore blasts. Unaware to Paramasivan, Nandakumar intends on killing him after the mission is completed.\n\nThe fly in the ointment is played by CBI officer Nair ([[Jayaram]]),  who is out to trace Paramasivan and stop his unlawful activities. His assistant SI Agniputran ([[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]]) provides lighter moments. How Paramasivan finishes the villains and his job forms the rest of the story. Paramasivan comes to know of Nandakumar's idea to kill him after the mission during the last few scenes where Nair intervenes. Eventually, Paramasivan is forgiven and starts a new life with his lover Malar ([[Laila Mehdin|Laila]]).\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Ajith Kumar]] as Subramaniyam Siva / Paramasivan / Eshwar\n* [[Laila Mehdin|Laila]] as Malar\n* [[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]] as SI Agniputran\n* [[Prakash Raj]] as SP 'Nethiadi' Nandakumar\n* [[Jayaram]] as CBI officer V. Nair\n* [[Nassar (actor)|Nassar]] as Vetrivel, police\n* [[Avinash]] as DGP Rajasekar\n* [[Kota Srinivasa Rao]] as Swamy Kathirvethi\n* [[Rajesh (actor)|Rajesh]] as SI Ganapathy, Subramaniyam Siva's father\n* [[Seetha (actress)|Seetha]] as Subramaniyam Siva's mother\n* [[Santhana Bharathi]] as Malar's father\n* [[Aishwarya Sivachandran|Ishwarya]] as Malar's stepmother\n* [[K. P. A. C. Lalitha|KPAC Lalitha]] as Malar's grandmother\n* [[Mayilsamy]] as Police Inspector\n* [[Sathyan Sivakumar|Sathyan]] as Police\n* [[R. S. Shivaji]] as Police\n* Cell Murugan as Sandeep Mususamy\n* [[Ragasya]] in an item number \n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\nAfter the success of ''[[Chandramukhi]]'' (2005), director [[P. Vasu]] announced his intentions of directing [[Rajinikanth]] again but the announcement of Rajinikanth's collaboration with [[S. Shankar|Shankar]] in ''[[Sivaji (film)|Sivaji]]'' hindered his hopes. In August 2005, he roped in [[Ajith Kumar]] to play the protagonist in his next film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ajithkumar.free.fr/news/news_180.htm |title=Rajini blessed for the success of Ajith's Thirupathi |publisher=www.ajithkumar.fr.fm |date=29 August 2005 |accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref> The project was initially taken up by director [[Bala (director)|Bala]]'s production house, B Studios, and was titled ''Idi'' (Thunder), with [[Laila Mehdin|Laila]] selected to play the leading female role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.apunkachoice.com/scoop/downsouth/tamil/20050906-0.html |title=Laila is back in Kollywood with a bang : Down South : Tamil News |publisher=ApunKaChoice.Com |date=26 January 2006 |accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref> The film was launched on 10 September 2005 by [[Rajinikanth]], while the title was changed to ''Paramasivan''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/features/News/News29/10-9-05e/tamil-movies-news-ajith.html |title=Tamil movies : It will be Paramasivan from P Vasu |publisher=Behindwoods |date=10 September 2005 |accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Ajith Kumar]]'s exit from Bala's directorial venture, ''[[Naan Kadavul]]'', this film changed producers the next month with S. Ramesh Babu agreeing to finance the film. [[Nisha Kothari]] was first requested to appear in an [[item number]] in the film but the role was later taken by [[Ragasya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ajithkumar.free.fr/news/news_189.htm |title=\"Jay Jay\" Amoga In Paramasivan? |publisher=www.ajithkumar.fr.fm |date=21 September 2005  |accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref> For the film, Ajith Kumar lost fifteen kilograms to get into shape.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/2006/jan/11vasu.htm |title=P Vasu: Ready for Paramasivan |publisher=Rediff|date= |accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref> [[K. Balachandar]]'s Kavithalaya Productions took up the distribution of ''Paramasivan'' for the Chengalpet area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/19707.html |title=A new role for old man&nbsp;\u2013 Tamil Movie News |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date=13 January 2006 |accessdate=18 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n\nBackground score and Songs composed by [[Vidyasagar (music director)|Vidyasagar]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tamilsonglyrics.org/movies/p-t/paramasivan-songs-lyrics/|title=Paramasivan songs lyrics |work=tamilsonglyrics|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623222731/http://www.tamilsonglyrics.org/movies/p-t/paramasivan-songs-lyrics/|archivedate=23 June 2015}}</ref>\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Paramasivan\n\n| type       = Paramasivan\n| artist     = Vidyasagar\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 2 January 2040\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[World Music]]\n| length     =\n| label      = The Best Audio\n| producer   = [[Vidyasagar (music director)|Vidyasagar]]\n| prev_title = [[Thambi (2006 film)|Thambi]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Aathi]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:70%;\"\n|-\n! Song Title !! Singers !! Lyrics\n|-\n| ''Oru Kili'' || [[Madhu Balakrishnan]], [[Sujatha Mohan|Sujatha]] || [[Yugabharathi]]\n|-\n| ''Aasai Dosai'' || Priya Subramani || [[Na. Muthukumar]]\n|-\n| ''Kannan'' || Kalyani Menon, Lakshmi Rangarajan, [[Saindhavi]] || Kirithaya\n|-\n| ''Natchathira Paravaikku'' || [[Tippu (singer)|Tippu]], Rajalakshmi || [[Vairamuthu]]\n|-\n| ''Thangakkili'' || [[Madhu Balakrishnan]], [[Gopika Poornima]], Srivarthini || Kirithaya\n|-\n| ''Undivila'' || [[Shankar Mahadevan]], [[Malathy Lakshman]] || [[P. Vijay]]\n|-\n| ''Paramasivane'' || [[Shankar Mahadevan]], Chandran, [[Karthik (singer)|Karthik]], [[Tippu (singer)|Tippu]], Jemon, [[Ranjith (singer)|Ranjith]] || [[Vairamuthu]]\n|-\n| ''Theme'' || Instrumental\n|}\n\n==Release==\nThe satellite rights of the film were sold to [[Jaya TV]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.in.com/tv/movies/jaya-tv-147/paramasivan-41367.html|title=LIVE TV - Watch Indian TV Channels - Live Streaming and Catchup TV - LIVE News Online - in.com|website=in.com}}</ref> It was dubbed into Hindi as ''Godfather Shiva''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9UryKHYuoNY|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Film|India}}\n* [[List of action films of the 2000s]]\n* [[List of Tamil films of 2006]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{AllRovi movie|342092}}\n* {{IMDb title|0816605}}\n\n{{P. Vasu}}\n\n[[Category:2000s action films]]\n[[Category:2006 films]]\n[[Category:Indian action films]]\n[[Category:Tamil remakes of Hindi films]]\n[[Category:Indian action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by P. Vasu]]\n[[Category:2000s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Tamil films scored by Vidyasagar]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Tamil Nadu Police]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Paramasivan\n| image          = Paramasivan.JPG\n| alt            = \n| director       = [[P. Vasu]]\n| producer       = S. Ramesh Babu\n| writer         = Pattukottai Prabakar'''(dialogues)'''\n| story          = [[Mahesh Bhatt]]\n| starring       = [[Ajith Kumar]]     \n  <br /> [[Laila Mehdin|Laila]]<br />[[Jayaram]]<br />[[Vivek (actor)|Vivek]]<br />[[Prakash Raj]]<br />\n| | music        = [[Vidyasagar (music director)|Vidyasagar]]\n| cinematography = [[Sekhar V. Joseph]]\n| editing        = [[Suresh Urs]]\n| studio         = Kanagarathna Movies<br />Samrat Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|2006|01|14|df=y